00:00:59.660 --> 00:01:00.480
JASON CALACANIS: Thanks
for having me, Heath.

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:02.354
We were journalists
together back in the day.

00:01:02.354 --> 00:01:03.510
HEATH ROWE: Yeah, we were.

00:01:03.510 --> 00:01:04.680
JASON CALACANIS:
Covering technology.

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:06.179
HEATH ROWE: Well,
let's start there,

00:01:06.179 --> 00:01:07.260
because I first met you--

00:01:07.260 --> 00:01:08.970
it wasn't photocopied
when I met you,

00:01:08.970 --> 00:01:10.440
but "Silicon Alley Reporter."

00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:13.530
You went on to "Digital
Coast Reporter," weblogs,

00:01:13.530 --> 00:01:15.510
Netscape, Mahalo.

00:01:15.510 --> 00:01:18.000
That journalism was
all generally focusing

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:21.900
on the gathering, curation,
and promotion of ideas,

00:01:21.900 --> 00:01:23.340
and powerful ideas.

00:01:23.340 --> 00:01:26.190
JASON CALACANIS: Yeah, I was
lucky enough to be in New York

00:01:26.190 --> 00:01:29.610
when the internet
hit in 1994 and '95.

00:01:29.610 --> 00:01:31.920
CD-ROMs were becoming a big
deal, multimedia, and then

00:01:31.920 --> 00:01:33.420
all of a sudden,
the internet became

00:01:33.420 --> 00:01:36.930
commercialized with the Netscape
browser supporting images.

00:01:36.930 --> 00:01:40.260
And I started a zine,
because back then,

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:43.170
if you wanted to be important
in the world, the real startup

00:01:43.170 --> 00:01:44.430
idea you had was a zine.

00:01:44.430 --> 00:01:46.772
And a zine just
meant a magazine that

00:01:46.772 --> 00:01:48.480
was not professionally
produced, but that

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:50.250
was literally a photocopy.

00:01:50.250 --> 00:01:52.950
And so after starting that
photocopy zine, "Silicon Alley

00:01:52.950 --> 00:01:56.280
Reporter," it quickly grew
into a print magazine.

00:01:56.280 --> 00:01:59.820
It had 300 pages, and I got
caught up in the whole dotcom

00:01:59.820 --> 00:02:01.570
sort of wave of innovation.

00:02:01.570 --> 00:02:03.870
And so I got very lucky,
but being a journalist

00:02:03.870 --> 00:02:07.440
is a great way to learn
how to interview founders

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:09.180
and to cut through BS.

00:02:09.180 --> 00:02:11.774
And you're kind of
a detective, right?

00:02:11.774 --> 00:02:13.190
Like when you're
a journalist, you

00:02:13.190 --> 00:02:16.514
have to ask questions,
let the person talk,

00:02:16.514 --> 00:02:18.430
and maybe try to figure
out what the truth is.

00:02:18.430 --> 00:02:20.638
And when you're an angel
investor, it's very similar.

00:02:20.638 --> 00:02:23.097
You're talking to founders,
and sometimes they're tourists.

00:02:23.097 --> 00:02:25.512
They're people who are just
trying on the concept of being

00:02:25.512 --> 00:02:26.230
a founder.

00:02:26.230 --> 00:02:28.645
They saw "The Social
Network," or they

00:02:28.645 --> 00:02:31.584
have seen how Uber, or
Google, or Airbnb have grown,

00:02:31.584 --> 00:02:32.750
and they say, I want to be--

00:02:32.750 --> 00:02:34.165
I want to be a founder.

00:02:34.165 --> 00:02:35.790
And then they start
pitching investors,

00:02:35.790 --> 00:02:37.998
and you realize, wow, this
person's going to give up.

00:02:37.998 --> 00:02:40.500
This idea does not have
real meaning to them,

00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:43.470
and they have no idea how
hard it is to be a founder.

00:02:43.470 --> 00:02:45.280
So I think that
journalism background

00:02:45.280 --> 00:02:47.780
has helped a number of people,
including Michael Moritz, who

00:02:47.780 --> 00:02:50.820
is the original investor
in Google was a journalist

00:02:50.820 --> 00:02:53.910
and wrote a book, actually,
about Apple back in the '80s.

00:02:53.910 --> 00:02:57.600
And so it's one of the great
paths I think to investing

00:02:57.600 --> 00:02:59.352
is either being a founder.

00:02:59.352 --> 00:03:00.810
Today you can be
a founder and then

00:03:00.810 --> 00:03:04.920
go on to be an investor,
or somebody in growth.

00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:06.510
That's another
big one right now.

00:03:06.510 --> 00:03:08.134
Everybody is looking
for growth hackers

00:03:08.134 --> 00:03:10.740
to become investors,
and the journalists.

00:03:10.740 --> 00:03:11.990
It used to be MBAs.

00:03:11.990 --> 00:03:14.640
You have to go get a Harvard
MBA, or Stanford MBA,

00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:18.300
and then your fraternity
brothers would get you

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:19.140
into a venture firm.

00:03:19.140 --> 00:03:22.009
Now, it's really delightful that
the whole model has flipped,

00:03:22.009 --> 00:03:24.300
and it's like if you don't
have operational experience,

00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:26.216
they really don't want
you in venture capital,

00:03:26.216 --> 00:03:30.540
and it used to be all venture
capitalists had zero operating

00:03:30.540 --> 00:03:33.690
experience, and they
were all finance,

00:03:33.690 --> 00:03:36.390
you know, MBA bros,
and all the firms

00:03:36.390 --> 00:03:40.117
were just groups of, you know,
Harvard and Stanford MBAs.

00:03:40.117 --> 00:03:41.200
Now, it's totally changed.

00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:43.980
They don't want to hire people
without operational experience,

00:03:43.980 --> 00:03:45.600
because the founders can
see through it immediately.

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:47.400
They're like you've
never run a company,

00:03:47.400 --> 00:03:48.816
and I'm going to
take your advice?

00:03:48.816 --> 00:03:50.730
I'm going to take
a pass on that.

00:03:50.730 --> 00:03:50.850
HEATH ROWE: Mhm.

00:03:50.850 --> 00:03:52.266
And what do you
think caused that?

00:03:52.266 --> 00:03:54.060
Or what happened in
the industry that

00:03:54.060 --> 00:03:56.669
led to that shift in thinking?

00:03:56.669 --> 00:03:58.710
JASON CALACANIS: The
founder-friendly movement, I

00:03:58.710 --> 00:04:00.960
think.

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:05.105
When a market gets hot,
and really Sean Parker--

00:04:05.105 --> 00:04:07.770
I would give Sean Parker
a lot of credit for it.

00:04:07.770 --> 00:04:11.040
You know, Sean Parker, and
Google, and Michael Moritz

00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:13.290
had a little bit of a back
and forth over Plaxo back

00:04:13.290 --> 00:04:14.400
in the day.

00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:18.029
And he then brought Zuckerberg
out to Silicon Valley

00:04:18.029 --> 00:04:21.057
and famously left
Sequoia at the altar

00:04:21.057 --> 00:04:22.890
and wouldn't let them
invest, because of how

00:04:22.890 --> 00:04:24.630
he felt he had been treated.

00:04:24.630 --> 00:04:28.080
And then Founders Fund,
Peter Thiel and Sean Parker

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:29.790
created Founders Fund.

00:04:29.790 --> 00:04:32.430
And the reason they named it
Founders Fund was specifically

00:04:32.430 --> 00:04:34.590
to attack Sequoia and
other venture firms

00:04:34.590 --> 00:04:38.280
and say, those firms are
interested in kicking out

00:04:38.280 --> 00:04:39.390
the founders.

00:04:39.390 --> 00:04:43.220
These firms are interested
in being founder friendly.

00:04:43.220 --> 00:04:45.330
And then that just changed
everybody's thinking.

00:04:45.330 --> 00:04:47.790
We have to be founder friendly.

00:04:47.790 --> 00:04:51.085
And you know, there's
pros and cons to it.

00:04:51.085 --> 00:04:53.460
HEATH ROWE: How do you balance
the operational experience

00:04:53.460 --> 00:04:56.680
with maybe an
idea-driven founder?

00:04:56.680 --> 00:04:59.460
JASON CALACANIS: Yeah
it's pretty interesting

00:04:59.460 --> 00:05:01.740
when you look at the
history of Silicon Valley.

00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:03.330
If you were to
say, I'm only going

00:05:03.330 --> 00:05:05.900
to invest in founders who
have great experience,

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:08.370
you would miss Larry and Sergey.

00:05:08.370 --> 00:05:11.389
You would have
missed Bill Gates,

00:05:11.389 --> 00:05:12.930
and you would have
missed Zuckerberg.

00:05:12.930 --> 00:05:15.150
You wouldn't have
missed, you know,

00:05:15.150 --> 00:05:18.940
Uber or some other company
that had serial founders.

00:05:18.940 --> 00:05:22.250
Twitter had a serial founder
obviously in Evan Williams.

00:05:22.250 --> 00:05:27.390
So there is actually a theory
that the biggest outcomes are

00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:29.430
by people who are first timers.

00:05:29.430 --> 00:05:31.470
It's not actually
backed up by reality.

00:05:31.470 --> 00:05:34.100
It's kind of 50/50.

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:36.780
But the thing about venture
capital and angel investing

00:05:36.780 --> 00:05:38.400
is you don't have
to hit everything.

00:05:38.400 --> 00:05:41.064
So if you missed Google,
and you get Facebook,

00:05:41.064 --> 00:05:43.230
or you get Facebook, and
you don't invest in Google,

00:05:43.230 --> 00:05:46.350
or you get Airbnb, and you don't
get Uber, all you have to do

00:05:46.350 --> 00:05:49.050
is hit one, and then they
let you write a book.

00:05:49.050 --> 00:05:53.760
I hit six unicorns in the
first 100 investments now.

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:55.710
When I wrote the book
and did the book deal,

00:05:55.710 --> 00:05:57.475
I had three unicorns.

00:05:57.475 --> 00:05:59.850
And since the book came out,
three of the other companies

00:05:59.850 --> 00:06:01.870
have tipped over
into that territory.

00:06:01.870 --> 00:06:04.590
So it's a pretty
good track record.

00:06:04.590 --> 00:06:06.630
But you know, the reason
I wrote the book really

00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:09.150
is it's so opaque the idea
of being an angel investor

00:06:09.150 --> 00:06:10.680
and doing it professionally.

00:06:10.680 --> 00:06:13.410
But because of large--

00:06:13.410 --> 00:06:15.900
the scale of internet
companies now

00:06:15.900 --> 00:06:17.940
and the amount of
wealth being created

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:19.800
has gotten so great
that now we went

00:06:19.800 --> 00:06:22.830
from just maybe 10 or 15
years ago, 10 years ago

00:06:22.830 --> 00:06:25.159
when I started angel investing--

00:06:25.159 --> 00:06:27.450
I started about seven years
ago, but about 10 years ago

00:06:27.450 --> 00:06:28.710
when I was a founder--

00:06:28.710 --> 00:06:31.500
raising money-- there was
only like a dozen or two dozen

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:32.525
angel investors of note.

00:06:32.525 --> 00:06:34.650
And you could kind of make
the rounds very quickly.

00:06:34.650 --> 00:06:37.980
Now, I'd say in
Silicon Valley, there

00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:43.797
are 500 to 1,000 people who
do it as a primary activity.

00:06:43.797 --> 00:06:45.630
In other words, they
spend 50% of their time

00:06:45.630 --> 00:06:46.839
on angel investing or more.

00:06:46.839 --> 00:06:49.380
So I think there's going to be
a professional angel investing

00:06:49.380 --> 00:06:50.550
class.

00:06:50.550 --> 00:06:52.680
The VCs have
retreated and said, we

00:06:52.680 --> 00:06:54.407
don't want to take risk anymore.

00:06:54.407 --> 00:06:56.490
We don't want to do a
series A that's speculative.

00:06:56.490 --> 00:06:59.130
Bring us companies, because
there is so many companies,

00:06:59.130 --> 00:07:00.130
they've moved
downstream and said,

00:07:00.130 --> 00:07:02.421
just bring us companies that
have revenue and traction.

00:07:02.421 --> 00:07:06.180
If it's an enterprise company
with $100,000 or $50,000

00:07:06.180 --> 00:07:08.250
a month, we'll meet with them.

00:07:08.250 --> 00:07:10.500
If it's a consumer
product, and it's

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:13.960
got 10,000 to 50,000
people using it a day,

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:16.255
and you've got three to
six months of traffic,

00:07:16.255 --> 00:07:18.630
we'll probably wait till you
hit 10 million users a month

00:07:18.630 --> 00:07:21.000
before we invest
and do a series A.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.030
But really, that's opened
up this huge swath of what

00:07:24.030 --> 00:07:25.950
I call the Goldilocks zone--

00:07:25.950 --> 00:07:28.320
pre-series A,
pre-venture capitalists

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:31.470
wanted to join the board, but
post the product being launched

00:07:31.470 --> 00:07:33.870
into the market, because
let's all face it,

00:07:33.870 --> 00:07:36.000
we know that you can get
any product to market,

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:37.950
or I'd say nine
out of 10 products,

00:07:37.950 --> 00:07:41.520
you can get some version of
it to market for either sweat

00:07:41.520 --> 00:07:44.320
equity or $100,000 or less.

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:44.820
Right?

00:07:44.820 --> 00:07:48.924
So if you wanted to build
Slack, or Twitter, or even Uber,

00:07:48.924 --> 00:07:50.340
you could do that
for low hundreds

00:07:50.340 --> 00:07:51.150
of thousands of dollars.

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:52.650
In other words,
people can bootstrap

00:07:52.650 --> 00:07:55.740
it, friends and family,
some close friends,

00:07:55.740 --> 00:07:57.960
to get that beta out.

00:07:57.960 --> 00:08:00.780
And that Goldilocks
zone is where

00:08:00.780 --> 00:08:03.180
I think a lot of
wealth creation is

00:08:03.180 --> 00:08:07.360
going to occur in the future,
because you've removed

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:11.610
the 99% of founders who never
get their product to market

00:08:11.610 --> 00:08:14.280
from your investment criteria.

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:19.380
And then you don't have the
VCs with their sharp elbows

00:08:19.380 --> 00:08:20.910
blocking the angel
investors yet.

00:08:20.910 --> 00:08:23.580
And that's just
probably a, I'll call it

00:08:23.580 --> 00:08:26.040
a three year window in
most startups, where

00:08:26.040 --> 00:08:27.381
angels can participate.

00:08:27.381 --> 00:08:29.130
There's probably about
four or five rounds

00:08:29.130 --> 00:08:31.030
of funding in there as well.

00:08:31.030 --> 00:08:36.390
Anybody here have a friend
who's actively running a startup

00:08:36.390 --> 00:08:38.909
and has raised money in
the last 12 months or so?

00:08:38.909 --> 00:08:40.740
Right, so almost
half of the room.

00:08:40.740 --> 00:08:42.570
And if you talk to
them, they probably

00:08:42.570 --> 00:08:45.270
will raise five rounds of
funding before a series

00:08:45.270 --> 00:08:47.850
A. It used to be you raised
an angel around, friends

00:08:47.850 --> 00:08:50.280
and family, an
angel or seed round,

00:08:50.280 --> 00:08:54.155
and then a series A. Now,
you raise friends and family

00:08:54.155 --> 00:08:58.650
that you do a pre-seed round,
a seed round, an angel round,

00:08:58.650 --> 00:09:01.349
a pre-series A, a
series A extension.

00:09:01.349 --> 00:09:03.390
They come up with all
these crazy names for them,

00:09:03.390 --> 00:09:08.550
but just call them $250,000
to $1.5 million rounds.

00:09:08.550 --> 00:09:11.040
And usually, there's
six convertible notes

00:09:11.040 --> 00:09:14.047
converting when they finally
get to series A, which

00:09:14.047 --> 00:09:16.380
means you can really take
your time as an angel investor

00:09:16.380 --> 00:09:18.030
and get to know the company.

00:09:18.030 --> 00:09:22.580
There is really no
need to panic and like,

00:09:22.580 --> 00:09:23.802
I have to get in this round.

00:09:23.802 --> 00:09:26.010
You can actually wait and
just build the relationship

00:09:26.010 --> 00:09:27.660
with the founders
over six months, which

00:09:27.660 --> 00:09:29.368
is kind of what I
outlined in the book is

00:09:29.368 --> 00:09:34.290
my theory on how to do it given
today's environment, which is--

00:09:34.290 --> 00:09:35.820
there's a lot of
startups, and they

00:09:35.820 --> 00:09:37.440
raise a lot of
rounds of funding,

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:40.446
and you really don't want
to be investing in startups

00:09:40.446 --> 00:09:41.820
before they finish
their product,

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:43.111
because it's a bit of a talent.

00:09:43.111 --> 00:09:46.440
You can't finish the product
without raising a ton of money,

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:49.382
maybe you're not
an actual builder.

00:09:49.382 --> 00:09:51.090
Sometimes it's true,
but most of the time

00:09:51.090 --> 00:09:52.740
you're not an actual builder.

00:09:52.740 --> 00:09:54.490
HEATH ROWE: Yeah, it's
'99 all over again.

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:55.948
JASON CALACANIS:
Basically, I mean,

00:09:55.948 --> 00:09:57.640
it is highly tourist
season right now.

00:09:57.640 --> 00:10:02.640
So the opportunity is still
very great, but a lot of people

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:05.720
are trying on and playing
the role of founder.

00:10:05.720 --> 00:10:09.370
And what they'll find is it's
a really, really difficult job.

00:10:09.370 --> 00:10:11.360
It's very hard to
be the founder.

00:10:11.360 --> 00:10:12.460
You don't sleep at night.

00:10:12.460 --> 00:10:17.140
You've got somewhere between six
weeks and 12 months of runway.

00:10:17.140 --> 00:10:21.820
Your product is probably under
assault from competitors,

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:24.760
and investors are
waiting to see,

00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:28.090
and people are deciding between
joining Facebook or Google

00:10:28.090 --> 00:10:30.524
and getting huge RSUs or
coming to your company.

00:10:30.524 --> 00:10:32.440
And you've got to convince
them, and then they

00:10:32.440 --> 00:10:34.210
come for six months and leave.

00:10:34.210 --> 00:10:35.710
So it's very hard.

00:10:35.710 --> 00:10:41.000
And I think that's one of the--

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.247
the interesting
parts of this is just

00:10:43.247 --> 00:10:45.580
trying to figure out who's
going to stick with the idea,

00:10:45.580 --> 00:10:47.860
because most days as a
founder, I would say,

00:10:47.860 --> 00:10:49.420
are not super rewarding.

00:10:49.420 --> 00:10:50.890
They are generally hard.

00:10:50.890 --> 00:10:53.850
The reward you get for being a
founder of a technology company

00:10:53.850 --> 00:10:56.140
is you hire the smartest
people you know,

00:10:56.140 --> 00:10:59.480
and they all bring you the
problems they can't solve.

00:10:59.480 --> 00:11:01.270
You know, so literally
every week, it's

00:11:01.270 --> 00:11:03.152
like, hey, we got
all this stuff done,

00:11:03.152 --> 00:11:04.610
but here's what we
didn't get done.

00:11:04.610 --> 00:11:05.630
Can you help us?

00:11:05.630 --> 00:11:06.130
Wow!

00:11:06.130 --> 00:11:06.921
That's challenging.

00:11:06.921 --> 00:11:09.324
You know, that's Elon's
life is like, OK,

00:11:09.324 --> 00:11:10.990
I hired the smartest
people in the room,

00:11:10.990 --> 00:11:14.380
and now they can't
figure out these things,

00:11:14.380 --> 00:11:18.840
and I've got to figure out how
to get the Model 3 out on time

00:11:18.840 --> 00:11:21.470
or get the Falcon to
