00:12:00.050 --> 00:12:02.200
And part of the reason
I wrote the book was I

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:04.270
think there's a lot of
people who have money

00:12:04.270 --> 00:12:05.920
in very boring asset classes.

00:12:05.920 --> 00:12:07.612
I call it dead money.

00:12:07.612 --> 00:12:09.320
You know, you've got
your money in bonds,

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:13.067
real estate, some equally
balanced equities portfolio,

00:12:13.067 --> 00:12:15.400
using Wealthfront, which is
a great tool for doing that.

00:12:15.400 --> 00:12:17.090
I'm an investor in that company.

00:12:17.090 --> 00:12:21.790
And so you have these swaths of
money that are sitting there,

00:12:21.790 --> 00:12:24.160
and it's not kind
of helping society

00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:26.020
in any way or changing things.

00:12:26.020 --> 00:12:28.390
I think people should take
maybe 5% of that net worth,

00:12:28.390 --> 00:12:30.730
10% of that net worth,
and put it in something

00:12:30.730 --> 00:12:32.020
that's highly risky.

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:33.640
It may not return--

00:12:33.640 --> 00:12:35.800
it may not have the
stability of, you know,

00:12:35.800 --> 00:12:37.630
the stock market
balanced portfolio

00:12:37.630 --> 00:12:40.600
that people talk about that
returns 4% to 7% a year

00:12:40.600 --> 00:12:43.300
and doubles every eight years.

00:12:43.300 --> 00:12:45.670
But you have that outside
chance of going at 100 to 1

00:12:45.670 --> 00:12:48.160
on an investment, or 1,000
to 1, which would then

00:12:48.160 --> 00:12:49.610
double your net worth.

00:12:49.610 --> 00:12:51.820
So I think people are
overly risk averse,

00:12:51.820 --> 00:12:54.970
and I try to outline in the
book, here's a strategy,

00:12:54.970 --> 00:12:56.440
maybe investing in syndicates.

00:12:56.440 --> 00:12:58.660
People know Angel
List, or Seed Invest,

00:12:58.660 --> 00:13:01.270
or I have my own syndicate
now, Jason Syndicate.

00:13:01.270 --> 00:13:03.970
People know that they can invest
alongside of angel investors.

00:13:03.970 --> 00:13:06.220
That's a great way to
learn how to do this.

00:13:06.220 --> 00:13:09.960
You're investing $1,000
or $3,000 in each startup,

00:13:09.960 --> 00:13:11.020
and you do 20 startups.

00:13:11.020 --> 00:13:14.280
All of a sudden, you may
have invested $60,000 total.

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:16.570
But you've done 30
investments, and you

00:13:16.570 --> 00:13:18.760
are watching the monthly
updates of 30 companies.

00:13:18.760 --> 00:13:20.218
It's a great way
to build a network

00:13:20.218 --> 00:13:22.720
and get in the game for what
most people would consider

00:13:22.720 --> 00:13:26.300
the price of one angel
investment, $50,000 or $60,000.

00:13:26.300 --> 00:13:29.440
So I try to outline all
of that in the book of how

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:31.850
to slowly learn how to do this.

00:13:31.850 --> 00:13:34.060
And I think it's probably
the most exciting career

00:13:34.060 --> 00:13:35.109
you could have.

00:13:35.109 --> 00:13:37.150
You get to hang out with
the smartest people, who

00:13:37.150 --> 00:13:39.620
want to change the
world, and meet them

00:13:39.620 --> 00:13:43.330
when they have 1 to 10
employees in their company.

00:13:43.330 --> 00:13:45.520
It's pretty exciting,
I have to say,

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:48.130
and even if you lost
half your money doing it,

00:13:48.130 --> 00:13:51.820
you'd be losing half of say
5% or 10% of your net worth.

00:13:51.820 --> 00:13:53.350
The network and
the knowledge you

00:13:53.350 --> 00:13:55.570
would build during
that time would easily

00:13:55.570 --> 00:13:57.404
make up for that 2.5%
of your net worth.

00:13:57.404 --> 00:13:59.320
HEATH ROWE: You're
smarter, bigger regardless.

00:13:59.320 --> 00:13:59.670
JASON CALACANIS: Yeah.

00:13:59.670 --> 00:14:00.060
And [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:00.060 --> 00:14:00.880
HEATH ROWE: That's
one of the things

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:03.700
I liked most about the book
was the kind of attitude

00:14:03.700 --> 00:14:05.890
of democratizing
angel investment.

00:14:05.890 --> 00:14:08.800
You mentioned earlier today
that there's a couple hundred

00:14:08.800 --> 00:14:10.115
angel investors in the valley.

00:14:10.115 --> 00:14:12.490
But this is saying that grandma
can be an angel investor.

00:14:12.490 --> 00:14:15.580
A college student can
be an angel investor.

00:14:15.580 --> 00:14:17.950
Talk us through some of
the steps or the advice

00:14:17.950 --> 00:14:19.905
that you would give people.

00:14:19.905 --> 00:14:23.049
JASON CALACANIS: Yeah, So I
think it's purposely opaque.

00:14:23.049 --> 00:14:25.090
We have a very unfair
system in the United States

00:14:25.090 --> 00:14:28.240
where there's two classes of
people, accredited investors

00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:30.040
and non-accredited.

00:14:30.040 --> 00:14:31.847
People who make
over $200,000 a year

00:14:31.847 --> 00:14:34.180
for a couple of years in a
row are considered accredited

00:14:34.180 --> 00:14:36.170
if they have $1 million
or $2 million in cash.

00:14:36.170 --> 00:14:38.200
You can look it up
on the SEC's website.

00:14:38.200 --> 00:14:39.760
And then the other
95% of America

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:41.650
are considered non-accredited.

00:14:41.650 --> 00:14:45.100
But those 95% can go to Vegas
and bet on a sports team,

00:14:45.100 --> 00:14:48.280
or they can play in their local
poker game, or they can buy,

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:52.240
you know, they can do whatever
they want with their money,

00:14:52.240 --> 00:14:54.152
using bad judgment, good
judgment, et cetera.

00:14:54.152 --> 00:14:56.110
They could even buy stocks
in the public market

00:14:56.110 --> 00:14:59.632
without having to
check with anybody.

00:14:59.632 --> 00:15:01.840
But the idea of investing
in private companies, which

00:15:01.840 --> 00:15:05.330
is where ultra wealth is
created, really outsized

00:15:05.330 --> 00:15:06.720
outcomes, is very--

00:15:06.720 --> 00:15:10.530
there's nowhere you can
have these kind of odds

00:15:10.530 --> 00:15:13.020
to get these kind of
returns except in Silicon

00:15:13.020 --> 00:15:14.340
Valley and startups.

00:15:14.340 --> 00:15:16.360
So I think that we'll
see that change.

00:15:16.360 --> 00:15:17.940
It's in Europe,
which is interesting,

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:19.606
because it's a pretty
protectionist kind

00:15:19.606 --> 00:15:22.470
of vibe over there obviously.

00:15:22.470 --> 00:15:25.037
They allow everybody to invest
their money however they want.

00:15:25.037 --> 00:15:27.120
So here in the United
States, we have a little bit

00:15:27.120 --> 00:15:29.820
of history of not trusting
people with their own money,

00:15:29.820 --> 00:15:30.990
but that's unraveling.

00:15:30.990 --> 00:15:33.510
It's good intention, but now
they have some actual equity

00:15:33.510 --> 00:15:36.840
crowdfunding, websites like
SeedInvest and Republic

00:15:36.840 --> 00:15:38.730
are taking companies
and allowing

00:15:38.730 --> 00:15:40.860
them to raise money
from civilians,

00:15:40.860 --> 00:15:43.480
non-accredited
investors for $500.

00:15:43.480 --> 00:15:45.340
So I look at it and
say, you know what?

00:15:45.340 --> 00:15:46.881
I see people out
there spending money

00:15:46.881 --> 00:15:48.510
on all kinds of dopey stuff.

00:15:48.510 --> 00:15:51.150
I think making investments in
startups would be a lot better.

00:15:51.150 --> 00:15:54.390
And if you were to ask
all of the Etsy sellers,

00:15:54.390 --> 00:15:57.780
early Etsy sellers, hey,
you're not accredited,

00:15:57.780 --> 00:16:01.030
but we have 5,000
creators on the platform.

00:16:01.030 --> 00:16:03.360
You could each invest up
to $1,000 in the platform.

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:04.890
How many of them
would have done it?

00:16:04.890 --> 00:16:06.900
And what kind of wealth
would be created?

00:16:06.900 --> 00:16:09.506
EBay, same story, think
about all the AdSense

00:16:09.506 --> 00:16:10.630
partners in the early days.

00:16:10.630 --> 00:16:12.150
If you had told me
when we were in Gadget

00:16:12.150 --> 00:16:13.380
is AdSense going to work?

00:16:13.380 --> 00:16:15.180
I was like, well, we're
making $3,000 a day

00:16:15.180 --> 00:16:18.240
off of it 10 years ago, I
would have made that bet

00:16:18.240 --> 00:16:22.440
and bought pre-public
Google shares for sure.

00:16:22.440 --> 00:16:24.480
But that opportunity
wasn't open to me.

00:16:24.480 --> 00:16:26.280
I wasn't accredited
yet at that time.

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:29.040
I was negative $10,000
actually in my bank account.

00:16:29.040 --> 00:16:30.390
So I was stuck.

00:16:30.390 --> 00:16:32.610
So I'm hoping that
all changes over time,

00:16:32.610 --> 00:16:36.240
and since I wrote the
book, it's been 25 days,

00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:38.850
we had 1,200 people in
our angel syndicate,

00:16:38.850 --> 00:16:41.940
and we've had 700 more joined.

00:16:41.940 --> 00:16:44.280
So we're averaging something
like 30 people a day

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:46.584
applying and then accepting
maybe half of them.

00:16:46.584 --> 00:16:48.750
And so I think this is going
to change in a big way.

00:16:48.750 --> 00:16:50.850
A company Cafe X, which
I'm an investor in,

00:16:50.850 --> 00:16:54.440
which is a robot
a coffee machine,

00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:57.960
who has raised two, not
equity crowdfunding,

00:16:57.960 --> 00:17:01.290
but two syndicates of note,
like upwards of a million

00:17:01.290 --> 00:17:04.530
from investors
$10,000 at a time.

00:17:04.530 --> 00:17:07.640
Now, we have hundreds of
investors on that [INAUDIBLE]

00:17:07.640 --> 00:17:11.250
table under one
umbrella, my syndicate.

00:17:11.250 --> 00:17:13.220
And all of those people
get to participate.

00:17:13.220 --> 00:17:14.220
I'm super proud of that.

00:17:14.220 --> 00:17:16.710
If that becomes a unicorn,
and those people turn $10,000,

00:17:16.710 --> 00:17:19.140
and it goes 100x,
I mean, I would

00:17:19.140 --> 00:17:21.780
be super excited to see
people become millionaires

00:17:21.780 --> 00:17:23.870
or to generate that
kind of wealth.

00:17:23.870 --> 00:17:24.869
And I've seen it happen.

00:17:24.869 --> 00:17:27.990
I mean, in Silicon Valley, I
see people who are pretty dopey

00:17:27.990 --> 00:17:30.570
make angel investments and
make millions of dollars

00:17:30.570 --> 00:17:32.390
pretty regularly.

00:17:32.390 --> 00:17:34.050
And it should be
open to more people,

00:17:34.050 --> 00:17:36.330
and most people have
a good eye for this.

00:17:36.330 --> 00:17:38.340
If you were to ask anybody
who was on LinkedIn

00:17:38.340 --> 00:17:43.260
in the first two years who were
recruiters, or HR executives,

00:17:43.260 --> 00:17:44.880
those HR executives
and recruiters

00:17:44.880 --> 00:17:46.470
who would normally
not have access

00:17:46.470 --> 00:17:47.790
had the inside information.

00:17:47.790 --> 00:17:50.130
They knew that LinkedIn
was going to become

00:17:50.130 --> 00:17:52.050
a very significant platform.

00:17:52.050 --> 00:17:54.300
The early creators
on YouTube knew

00:17:54.300 --> 00:17:56.050
that it was going to
be something special.

00:17:56.050 --> 00:17:59.280
It was obvious to them, but they
could not participate into it.

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:01.980
And Chad would have absolutely
allowed YouTube creators

00:18:01.980 --> 00:18:04.092
to invest if that was allowed.

00:18:04.092 --> 00:18:06.300
And that's what we're slowly
starting to have happen.

00:18:06.300 --> 00:18:07.850
It started last June.

00:18:07.850 --> 00:18:09.142
And it's been a year.

00:18:09.142 --> 00:18:10.850
The companies that
are doing equity crowd

00:18:10.850 --> 00:18:14.170
funding I would say are the--

00:18:14.170 --> 00:18:16.170
in some cases, the ones
that didn't clear market

00:18:16.170 --> 00:18:18.174
with venture capitalists angels.

00:18:18.174 --> 00:18:19.590
But I think that's
slowly starting

00:18:19.590 --> 00:18:23.876
to change where the scariness of
doing something new, like angel

00:18:23.876 --> 00:18:26.250
with syndicates was very new,
and people were very scared

00:18:26.250 --> 00:18:28.170
of it, that's flipped over.

00:18:28.170 --> 00:18:32.010
So if everybody were to
invest 5% of their net worth

00:18:32.010 --> 00:18:34.610
in startups, I think the world
will get better a lot quicker,

00:18:34.610 --> 00:18:36.330
it would create a lot
more jobs, and we'd

00:18:36.330 --> 00:18:37.955
see a lot more problems
getting solved.

00:18:37.955 --> 00:18:40.410
So I actually believe that
this is something bigger

00:18:40.410 --> 00:18:41.470
than just making money.

00:18:41.470 --> 00:18:42.730
I think it's making
change in the world.

00:18:42.730 --> 00:18:45.270
If you think about all the
great change that's occurred,

00:18:45.270 --> 00:18:47.940
it's because some angel
investors supported

00:18:47.940 --> 00:18:51.390
some crazy kids who had some
crazy idea, whether it was

00:18:51.390 --> 00:18:55.020
Larry and Sergey, or Chad,
and the team at YouTube,

00:18:55.020 --> 00:19:00.180
or Snapchat, and they all needed
some small amount of money

00:19:00.180 --> 00:19:01.080
to get going.

00:19:01.080 --> 00:19:02.850
And these experiments
are worth trying,

00:19:02.850 --> 00:19:07.380
and if you lose, you know,
6, 7, 8, or 9 out of 10 bets,

00:19:07.380 --> 00:19:11.280
and the last bet returns more
than 10x, you're in the black.

00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:16.320
And just as a gambler myself,
as a semi-professional gambler,

00:19:16.320 --> 00:19:19.680
in fact, like high
stakes gambler in poker,

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:24.600
it's very hard for people
to deal with losing

00:19:24.600 --> 00:19:26.850
six or seven hands in a row.

00:19:26.850 --> 00:19:28.410
Anybody here play poker?

00:19:28.410 --> 00:19:30.300
Anybody here ever lose
seven or eight hands

00:19:30.300 --> 00:19:32.820
in a row when they
were the odds favorite?

00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:34.410
Yes, people are
raising their hand.

00:19:34.410 --> 00:19:36.810
I mean, it's going to happen
one out of every 500 games

00:19:36.810 --> 00:19:37.950
you play, right?

00:19:37.950 --> 00:19:40.750
And when you're not ready for
it, you stare at the ceiling

00:19:40.750 --> 00:19:43.139
and go, how did I lose
all of those hands?

00:19:43.139 --> 00:19:45.180
I lost six hands in a row
that I should have won.

00:19:45.180 --> 00:19:47.520
It's a very odd feeling.

00:19:47.520 --> 00:19:49.929
That's actually normal
for angel investing

00:19:49.929 --> 00:19:50.970
if you're doing it right.

00:19:50.970 --> 00:19:57.600
Like when I introduced people
to Uber, 17 of 22 or 23,

00:19:57.600 --> 00:20:00.870
only three people said yes
out of maybe 20 or 25 people

00:20:00.870 --> 00:20:01.890
I introduced them to.

00:20:01.890 --> 00:20:03.806
And we're talking about
the greatest investors

00:20:03.806 --> 00:20:05.390
in the world said no to Uber.

00:20:05.390 --> 00:20:07.930
And they said no
two or three times.

00:20:07.930 --> 00:20:10.510
And the three people
who said yes all

00:20:10.510 --> 00:20:12.760
have nine-figure positions.

00:20:12.760 --> 00:20:15.917
And the people who said no, some
of have 10-figure positions.

00:20:15.917 --> 00:20:18.250
Some of the people said no,
just every time they see me,

00:20:18.250 --> 00:20:19.583
they go, I should have listened.

00:20:19.583 --> 00:20:23.797
And the list of reasons of why a
startup will fail is very long.

00:20:23.797 --> 00:20:26.380
And the list of reasons of why
it will succeed are very short.

00:20:26.380 --> 00:20:30.250
And so what I've learned to do
is work against my natural--

00:20:30.250 --> 00:20:34.330
our biological nature is to be
conservative as humans, right?

00:20:34.330 --> 00:20:36.684
If you were to swim
across the river,

00:20:36.684 --> 00:20:39.100
the river might take you, or
the alligator might take you.

00:20:39.100 --> 00:20:41.440
Or if you go over the hill,
the lion might eat you.

00:20:41.440 --> 00:20:45.610
We are conservative
animals for good reason.

00:20:45.610 --> 00:20:47.750
But we don't need to be
conservative in this aspect

00:20:47.750 --> 00:20:48.250
of our life.

00:20:48.250 --> 00:20:49.620
We should be risk taking.

00:20:49.620 --> 00:20:51.820
But risk taking is
something that people just

00:20:51.820 --> 00:20:53.700
don't have in their DNA.

00:20:53.700 --> 00:20:56.191
So you have to unlearn what
your DNA is telling you.

00:20:56.191 --> 00:20:57.440
You should be taken this risk.

00:20:57.440 --> 00:20:59.315
There is no crocodile
that's going to eat you

00:20:59.315 --> 00:21:00.357
if you lose your $10,000.

00:21:00.357 --> 00:21:01.731
You're just going
to lose $10,000

00:21:01.731 --> 00:21:02.960
and make it back next month.

00:21:02.960 --> 00:21:03.960
So don't worry about it.

00:21:03.960 --> 00:21:05.300
It's fine to burn that $10,000.

00:21:05.300 --> 00:21:07.180
It's a worthwhile risk.

00:21:07.180 --> 00:21:10.461
And people overestimate the
downsides so much it's crazy.

00:21:10.461 --> 00:21:11.960
HEATH ROWE: Let's
unpack that a bit.

