to $1,000 a day

00:51:43.910 --> 00:51:45.960
and profits, whatever it is.

00:51:45.960 --> 00:51:48.950
And so, again, most
people overthink it,

00:51:48.950 --> 00:51:51.080
and the whole industry
is cracked wide open,

00:51:51.080 --> 00:51:54.734
because of AngelList, and
SeedInvest, and the reason

00:51:54.734 --> 00:51:56.150
I wrote the book
was really to try

00:51:56.150 --> 00:51:58.880
to inspire people to
get involved in it

00:51:58.880 --> 00:52:00.500
and not overthink it.

00:52:00.500 --> 00:52:05.610
Investing and losing 1% of your
net worth, if you learn a ton,

00:52:05.610 --> 00:52:07.762
it's going to be well
worth it in my mind.

00:52:07.762 --> 00:52:08.970
AUDIENCE: A quick follow up--

00:52:08.970 --> 00:52:11.100
thinking about this.

00:52:11.100 --> 00:52:12.830
On overthinking, do
you try to time it

00:52:12.830 --> 00:52:15.792
in terms of, well, this thing--

00:52:15.792 --> 00:52:17.750
there's been not enough
false starts quite yet?

00:52:17.750 --> 00:52:20.090
Or there's a paradigm
shift, and I really

00:52:20.090 --> 00:52:22.490
should be looking
in this direction?

00:52:22.490 --> 00:52:25.510
JASON CALACANIS: Yeah, don't
overthink it is what I think.

00:52:25.510 --> 00:52:30.170
To the Twitter
example, I understood

00:52:30.170 --> 00:52:33.830
it could become a huge
cacophony of idiots.

00:52:33.830 --> 00:52:35.240
Yet I missed the obvious.

00:52:35.240 --> 00:52:37.940
If it does, who cares
if they're idiots,

00:52:37.940 --> 00:52:41.060
or geniuses, whatever
it is, it's a big thing.

00:52:41.060 --> 00:52:43.340
And big things in the world
generate tons of wealth,

00:52:43.340 --> 00:52:46.430
and this thing also, in addition
to being a place for idiots

00:52:46.430 --> 00:52:49.569
to spew hate, is a place where
revolutions can start, right?

00:52:49.569 --> 00:52:51.860
AUDIENCE: So you're saying
that if you don't personally

00:52:51.860 --> 00:52:54.740
like something, that shouldn't
be a barrier toward--

00:52:54.740 --> 00:52:57.350
JASON CALACANIS: I think you
have to let go of your ego,

00:52:57.350 --> 00:52:59.240
and what you think
of the idea, and what

00:52:59.240 --> 00:53:02.430
you think of the possibility
that it could work.

00:53:02.430 --> 00:53:05.300
Now, if you're offended by
the existence of something,

00:53:05.300 --> 00:53:06.080
then I don't think
you should invest.

00:53:06.080 --> 00:53:07.120
You're not enthusiastic.

00:53:07.120 --> 00:53:08.380
But I'll give another example.

00:53:08.380 --> 00:53:10.850
I didn't have a chance
to invest in Airbnb.

00:53:10.850 --> 00:53:13.520
But I thought when I
heard the Airbnb idea,

00:53:13.520 --> 00:53:16.060
I literally said to people,
they were like, yeah,

00:53:16.060 --> 00:53:17.060
you can rent your couch.

00:53:17.060 --> 00:53:17.840
It's like couchsurfing.

00:53:17.840 --> 00:53:19.670
So you let somebody
sleep on your couch.

00:53:19.670 --> 00:53:21.635
And I'm like, like
a serial killer?

00:53:21.635 --> 00:53:23.510
So I'd let a serial
killer sleep on my couch?

00:53:23.510 --> 00:53:24.670
They're like, no,
no, no, no no no.

00:53:24.670 --> 00:53:26.128
They're all like,
it's a community.

00:53:26.128 --> 00:53:28.000
And I'm like, of serial killers?

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:29.529
They're like, no, it's not.

00:53:29.529 --> 00:53:31.070
Or you could stay
on somebody's couch

00:53:31.070 --> 00:53:33.597
for like $50 or $30
bucks, if you go to--

00:53:33.597 --> 00:53:35.180
if you couldn't
afford to go to Paris,

00:53:35.180 --> 00:53:38.720
you could stay in Paris for
$30 on a serial killer's couch.

00:53:38.720 --> 00:53:41.249
Like how many people here
have stayed in an Airbnb?

00:53:41.249 --> 00:53:43.040
Raise your hand if you
stayed in an Airbnb?

00:53:43.040 --> 00:53:44.100
It's everybody.

00:53:44.100 --> 00:53:46.580
How many people have hosted
somebody as an Airbnb host?

00:53:46.580 --> 00:53:48.496
Raise your hand if you've
done an Airbnb host.

00:53:48.496 --> 00:53:49.060
One person.

00:53:49.060 --> 00:53:53.416
OK, how do you--

00:53:53.416 --> 00:53:55.040
I could never have
somebody in my house

00:53:55.040 --> 00:53:56.248
who I don't know and do this.

00:53:56.248 --> 00:53:58.280
Like I'm just not brave
enough to do that.

00:53:58.280 --> 00:54:00.440
And sure enough,
I was like, how do

00:54:00.440 --> 00:54:02.294
you stop a meth head
from renting a place,

00:54:02.294 --> 00:54:03.710
and just tearing
it to the ground,

00:54:03.710 --> 00:54:05.626
and ripping it apart,
and having a meth party.

00:54:05.626 --> 00:54:08.046
And sure enough, in a year
two of Airbnb, it was like,

00:54:08.046 --> 00:54:09.920
there was a meth party
at this woman's house,

00:54:09.920 --> 00:54:11.180
and they took all
her photos, and they

00:54:11.180 --> 00:54:13.640
made their own collages,
and put like, kill everybody

00:54:13.640 --> 00:54:16.550
on the walls, and it was like
the most horrific horror movie

00:54:16.550 --> 00:54:17.450
ever.

00:54:17.450 --> 00:54:19.474
And I was like, yep,
just like a hotel room.

00:54:19.474 --> 00:54:20.390
I was like, oh, I see.

00:54:20.390 --> 00:54:21.860
I overthought it.

00:54:21.860 --> 00:54:26.210
Like there's 20 meth
parties going on right now

00:54:26.210 --> 00:54:27.410
in hotels in Los Angeles.

00:54:27.410 --> 00:54:29.040
We are not aware of them.

00:54:29.040 --> 00:54:32.330
But this is what
people do in hotels.

00:54:32.330 --> 00:54:34.157
There's meth parties
going on, I guess.

00:54:34.157 --> 00:54:35.990
So of course it's going
to happen to Airbnb,

00:54:35.990 --> 00:54:36.865
and there's whatever.

00:54:36.865 --> 00:54:39.470
So you have to be able to like,
again, write the long list

00:54:39.470 --> 00:54:40.970
of why it's not going to work.

00:54:40.970 --> 00:54:42.344
There's going to
be a meth party.

00:54:42.344 --> 00:54:44.810
Or somebody is in it
tragically-- you know,

00:54:44.810 --> 00:54:46.880
a ride sharing service
is going to flip a car,

00:54:46.880 --> 00:54:48.800
and people are going to die.

00:54:48.800 --> 00:54:50.960
Or an airplane is going to die.

00:54:50.960 --> 00:54:53.021
People are going to
die in an airplane.

00:54:53.021 --> 00:54:54.770
I just couldn't get
through it in my mind,

00:54:54.770 --> 00:54:57.950
so I think sometimes, taking
yourself and your understanding

00:54:57.950 --> 00:54:59.870
of the issue in the
market out of it

00:54:59.870 --> 00:55:01.737
and just looking
at the founder--

00:55:01.737 --> 00:55:02.570
are they passionate?

00:55:02.570 --> 00:55:04.490
And are they making
a great product?

00:55:04.490 --> 00:55:07.073
If they're able to make a great
product, and their passionate,

00:55:07.073 --> 00:55:10.130
and they're smart, well, if the
product doesn't get that uptick

00:55:10.130 --> 00:55:12.440
from users, they're probably
going to pivot a bit

00:55:12.440 --> 00:55:14.780
and figure out another product.

00:55:14.780 --> 00:55:18.830
Whereas a team of idiots who
have a great story about how

00:55:18.830 --> 00:55:20.300
big the market
is, but they can't

00:55:20.300 --> 00:55:23.970
build a really great product,
they're not going to succeed.

00:55:23.970 --> 00:55:25.387
They're just not
going to succeed.

00:55:25.387 --> 00:55:26.011
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:55:26.011 --> 00:55:26.620
Thanks.

00:55:26.620 --> 00:55:27.500
JASON CALACANIS: I think
you have a question here.

00:55:27.500 --> 00:55:28.240
HEATHE ROWE: You have
a hand in the back.

00:55:28.240 --> 00:55:30.399
JASON CALACANIS: I'll
do shorter answers.

00:55:30.399 --> 00:55:31.940
AUDIENCE: Yeah, what
about the people

00:55:31.940 --> 00:55:34.080
raising money with
virtual currency now?

00:55:34.080 --> 00:55:36.050
JASON CALACANIS: It's
a great question.

00:55:36.050 --> 00:55:38.070
I have looked at the companies.

00:55:38.070 --> 00:55:43.310
And I would say the first wave
of ICOs are extremely scary.

00:55:43.310 --> 00:55:47.570
It reminds me of the dotcom
bubble, so I'd be very careful.

00:55:47.570 --> 00:55:50.480
People who have
crazy ideas, have not

00:55:50.480 --> 00:55:53.510
built them, raising $30
million or $100 million,

00:55:53.510 --> 00:55:56.480
is a recipe for disaster.

00:55:56.480 --> 00:55:58.790
In the height of
the dotcom boom,

00:55:58.790 --> 00:56:02.630
we had people raising money or
taking companies public based

00:56:02.630 --> 00:56:04.547
on the idea that they
would raise $100 million

00:56:04.547 --> 00:56:06.463
and then figure out what
to do with it, right?

00:56:06.463 --> 00:56:08.300
There was a company
called CMGI, I remember,

00:56:08.300 --> 00:56:09.530
that was like an incubator.

00:56:09.530 --> 00:56:11.960
And all these companies were
going public with the idea

00:56:11.960 --> 00:56:13.692
that they would
create companies.

00:56:13.692 --> 00:56:15.150
So you have people
who are creating

00:56:15.150 --> 00:56:18.320
ICOs for products that don't
exist that are crazy ideas.

00:56:18.320 --> 00:56:19.250
Will one of them work?

00:56:19.250 --> 00:56:19.749
Sure.

00:56:19.749 --> 00:56:20.720
Will 99 of them fail?

00:56:20.720 --> 00:56:21.890
Probably

00:56:22.460 --> 00:56:24.680
And then where is this
money coming from?

00:56:24.680 --> 00:56:28.070
And this money is dark money
from I think the crypto boom.

00:56:28.070 --> 00:56:31.430
So people have a ton of
Ethereum, or a ton of Bitcoin,

00:56:31.430 --> 00:56:34.370
and like, OK, I'll diversify,
so I'll buy all these ICOs.

00:56:34.370 --> 00:56:36.800
It feels like the ultimate
Ponzi scheme to me.

00:56:36.800 --> 00:56:39.090
It's real technology.

00:56:39.090 --> 00:56:40.520
It could have a real impact.

00:56:40.520 --> 00:56:42.070
But this early cohort--

00:56:42.070 --> 00:56:45.050
I would not be surprised
if almost all of them

00:56:45.050 --> 00:56:47.520
went to zero, and all of
that money got burned,

00:56:47.520 --> 00:56:50.372
and there were massive
lawsuits around it,

00:56:50.372 --> 00:56:52.580
and that there was massive
fraud occurring right now.

00:56:52.580 --> 00:56:57.680
I believe Bitcoin is probably
one of the most massively

00:56:57.680 --> 00:57:00.830
manipulated currencies in
the world or most manipulated

00:57:00.830 --> 00:57:02.160
things in the world.

00:57:02.160 --> 00:57:04.730
What's to stop somebody from
creating 100,000 wallets,

00:57:04.730 --> 00:57:06.950
or 10 of us from creating
100,000 wallets each,

00:57:06.950 --> 00:57:09.500
and moving a bunch
of bitcoins around

00:57:09.500 --> 00:57:11.630
and making it look like
there's all this volume,

00:57:11.630 --> 00:57:15.140
and then making the
share price go up?

00:57:15.140 --> 00:57:17.240
There's a lot of
ability to manipulate

00:57:17.240 --> 00:57:18.980
anonymous currencies.

00:57:18.980 --> 00:57:22.864
And the SEC is not very--

00:57:22.864 --> 00:57:25.280
we talked a little bit earlier
about non-accredited versus

00:57:25.280 --> 00:57:25.850
accredited.

00:57:25.850 --> 00:57:31.330
The SEC, they do not have a--

00:57:31.330 --> 00:57:32.870
what's the right way to say it?

00:57:32.870 --> 00:57:37.580
They're not looking
for creative solutions

00:57:37.580 --> 00:57:41.430
to be put into the market
with people's money at risk.

00:57:41.430 --> 00:57:42.320
They're risk averse.

00:57:42.320 --> 00:57:44.930
Their whole reason to
exist is to protect people

00:57:44.930 --> 00:57:47.862
from losing their money
and being tricked.

00:57:47.862 --> 00:57:49.820
These things seem like
people could get tricked

00:57:49.820 --> 00:57:50.945
and could lose their money.

00:57:50.945 --> 00:57:54.439
And then a lot of people are
like, it's not an offering.

00:57:54.439 --> 00:57:55.730
It's not like a stock offering.

00:57:55.730 --> 00:57:57.170
And then the people
buying it are buying it.

00:57:57.170 --> 00:57:59.060
When you ask them why
are they buying it?

00:57:59.060 --> 00:58:01.420
They're saying, because it's
going to go up in value.

00:58:01.420 --> 00:58:03.920
If the people buying it
believe it's a security,

00:58:03.920 --> 00:58:05.900
and you are pretending
it's not while you're

00:58:05.900 --> 00:58:08.970
cashing in tens of
millions of dollars,

00:58:08.970 --> 00:58:11.290
this is, I think, disingenuous.

00:58:11.290 --> 00:58:14.810
So some people who are
taking in the money in I know

00:58:14.810 --> 00:58:18.200
are doing things like
paying taxes on it,

00:58:18.200 --> 00:58:20.570
saying it's future
revenue for software,

00:58:20.570 --> 00:58:22.372
because this is our
API calls or whatever.

00:58:22.372 --> 00:58:24.080
So they're actually
going pay their taxes

00:58:24.080 --> 00:58:27.260
on it-- pay as if it's profits
against software revenues.

00:58:27.260 --> 00:58:29.120
So I think that's smart.

00:58:29.120 --> 00:58:32.930
I do think that the fund,
having a venture fund, where

00:58:32.930 --> 00:58:36.800
the LP interests, the Limited
Partners are in coins and are

00:58:36.800 --> 00:58:37.984
on a ledger, is inevitable.

00:58:37.984 --> 00:58:40.400
And that people will then be
able to trade their interest.

00:58:40.400 --> 00:58:42.320
So if you were in
the Sequoia Fund

00:58:42.320 --> 00:58:45.080
with Google at the IPO
or right before the IPO,

00:58:45.080 --> 00:58:47.450
and you wanted to sell your
shares to another person

00:58:47.450 --> 00:58:50.300
or your benchmark right now in
the Uber situation where Uber

00:58:50.300 --> 00:58:52.650
and Benchmark are fighting.

00:58:52.650 --> 00:58:55.700
If Benchmark shares
were freely tradeable,

00:58:55.700 --> 00:58:57.530
and the LPs could
trade them, well, they

00:58:57.530 --> 00:58:58.730
might liquidate right now.

00:58:58.730 --> 00:59:02.180
Or they might be wanting to
buy from another party, right?

00:59:02.180 --> 00:59:03.990
And so you would have
this more fluidity.

00:59:03.990 --> 00:59:06.830
So I do think that that will
come very quickly, like two

00:59:06.830 --> 00:59:09.500
or three years, and other
countries are going to lead it,

00:59:09.500 --> 00:59:11.791
because we are very conservative
when it comes to this.

00:59:11.791 --> 00:59:14.630
So I think
Scandinavian countries,

00:59:14.630 --> 00:59:18.410
and Asian countries,
not companies,

00:59:18.410 --> 00:59:20.090
are going to be
very fluid with it.

00:59:20.090 --> 00:59:24.830
But I'm monitoring it, because
you know, if you were a fund--

00:59:24.830 --> 00:59:27.920
if you have funds like
I have had, or have,

00:59:27.920 --> 00:59:30.300
it's an interesting concept.

00:59:30.300 --> 00:59:33.630
I'm certainly a believer
in the technology.

00:59:33.630 --> 00:59:35.550
But I also saw a
lot of companies,

00:59:35.550 --> 00:59:38.150
I think, in that group,
that I just thought,

00:59:38.150 --> 00:59:40.885
they could not clear a market
with the venture community.

00:59:40.885 --> 00:59:43.010
That doesn't mean the
venture community is perfect,

00:59:43.010 --> 00:59:44.190
or the angel
community is perfect,

00:59:44.190 --> 00:59:45.934
but they tend to know
what they're doing.

00:59:45.934 --> 00:59:47.600
And that machine is
a well-oiled machine

00:59:47.600 --> 00:59:49.530
that knows how to take risks.

00:59:49.530 --> 00:59:51.890
So if the well-oiled
machine of Silicon Valley,

00:59:51.890 --> 00:59:54.200
and venture money,
and angel money

00:59:54.200 --> 00:59:56.280
passed on investing
in these companies,

00:59:56.280 --> 00:59:58.760
and then they were able to
raise from dark pools of capital

00:59:58.760 --> 01:00:03.145
of unsophisticated
people, I don't know.

01:00:03.145 --> 01:00:05.270
I don't know if there's
that much wisdom in crowds.

01:00:05.270 --> 01:00:06.354
I'm very worried about it.

